See Also:</Font>  Other Worksheets in the same package.</Font></Text-field><Text-field layout="Share Details" style="Share Details"><Font family="Times New Roman" style="_cstyle264">Prerequisites:</Font><Font family="Times New Roman">  none</Font></Text-field><Text-field layout="Share Details" style="Share Details"><Font family="Times New Roman" style="_cstyle262">Note:</Font><Font family="Times New Roman">  Send me an e-mail (comments-criticisms) if you use this worksheet.</Font></Text-field><Text-field layout="Normal" style="Normal"/><Text-field layout="Normal" style="Normal"/></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input">restart;assume(n,integer):with(plots):
setoptions(thickness=2): #set the tickness of the lines in the plots</Text-field></Input></Group><Section collapsed="true"><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 1" style="Heading 1"><Font family="Times New Roman">Introduction</Font></Text-field></Title><Group><Input><Text-field layout="_pstyle260" style="_pstyle260"><Font family="Times New Roman">I show how to compute <Font style="_cstyle268">Fourier integrals</Font> and how to approximate the function by taking a finite domain of integration. I look at the approximation as the domain of integration increases (Animation!).
</Font></Text-field></Input></Group></Section><Section collapsed="true"><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 1" style="Heading 1"><Font family="Times New Roman">Section 1:  The square pulse </Font></Text-field></Title><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input">f:=(signum(-x^2+1)+1)/2;g:=(signum(-x^2+1)+1.001)/2:</Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input">plot( g,x=-5..5,title="The square pulse");</Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" style="Normal"><Font family="Times New Roman">The function </Font><Equation input-equation="A(omega)" style="2D Comment">NiMtJSJBRzYjJSZvbWVnYUc=</Equation></Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input">A:=1/Pi*Int('f'*cos(omega*x),x=-infinity..infinity);
A:=1/Pi*int(f*cos(omega*x),x=-infinity..infinity);</Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" style="Normal"><Font family="Times New Roman">The function </Font><Equation input-equation="B(omega);" style="2D Comment">NiMtJSJCRzYjJSZvbWVnYUc=</Equation></Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input">B:=1/Pi*Int('f'*sin(omega*x),x=-infinity..infinity);
B:=1/Pi*int(f*sin(omega*x),x=-infinity..infinity);</Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" style="Normal"><Font family="Times New Roman">The function </Font><Equation input-equation="B(omega)" style="2D Comment">NiMtJSJCRzYjJSZvbWVnYUc=</Equation><Font family="Times New Roman"> is zero since the function </Font><Equation input-equation="f" style="2D Comment">NiMlImZH</Equation><Font family="Times New Roman"> is even!</Font></Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" style="Normal"><Font family="Times New Roman">Now we can represent the function f by its fourier integral:</Font></Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="_pstyle256" style="2D Comment"><Equation input-equation="f = int(A*cos(omega*x)+B*sin(omega*x),x = 0 .. infinity);" style="2D Comment">NiMvJSJmRy0lJGludEc2JCwmKiYlIkFHIiIiLSUkY29zRzYjKiYlJm9tZWdhR0YrJSJ4R0YrRitGKyomJSJCR0YrLSUkc2luR0YuRitGKy9GMTsiIiElKWluZmluaXR5Rw==</Equation></Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" style="Normal"><Font family="Times New Roman">Let us look at some coefficients </Font><Equation input-equation="b[k]" style="2D Comment">NiMmJSJiRzYjJSJrRw==</Equation></Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input">F := int(A*cos(omega*x)+B*sin(omega*x),omega = 0 .. infinity);</Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" style="Normal"><Font family="Times New Roman">Consider now the approximation of f obtained by integrating to L with L increasing:</Font></Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input">F := int(A*cos(omega*x)+B*sin(omega*x),omega = 0 .. L);</Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input">plot({f,subs(L=2,F)},x=-5..5,title="First approximation (L=2)");</Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" style="Normal"><Font family="Times New Roman">This is not very good. Let us see L=4,8,16,32</Font></Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input">plot([f,subs(L=4,F),subs(L=8,F),subs(L=16,F)],x=-5..5,title="Higher approximation (L=4,8,16,32)",color=[red,green,blue,magenta],numpoints=150);</Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input">plot({f,subs(L=256,F)},x=-5..5,title="Higher approximation (L=256)",color=[red,blue],numpoints=150);</Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" style="Normal"><Font family="Times New Roman">The approximation gets better. Observe again the Gibbs phenomenom. The oscillations around the points of discontinuity.</Font></Text-field></Input></Group><Section><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 2" style="Heading 2"><Font family="Times New Roman">An animation</Font></Text-field></Title><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" style="Normal"><Font family="Times New Roman">We can see how the approximation gets better by looking at all the graphs as L increases:</Font></Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input">for i from 1 by 1 to 64 do
  p[i]:=display(plot(subs(L=i,F),x=-5..5,-0.2..1.2,color=red,numpoints=150),
  PLOT(TEXT([-4,1],cat("(L=",i,")"),COLOR(RGB,0,0,1)))):
od:</Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input">display([seq(p[i],i=1..64)],insequence=true);</Text-field><Text-field layout="Maple Plot" style="Maple Plot"/></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"/></Input></Group></Section></Section><Section><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 1" style="Heading 1"><Font family="Times New Roman"> References</Font></Text-field></Title><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" style="Normal"><Font family="Times New Roman">E. Kreyszig : <Font style="_cstyle269">Advanced Engineering Mathematics (8th Edition) </Font>John Wiley  New York (1999)</Font></Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="AC - Disclaimer" style="AC - Disclaimer"><Font family="Times New Roman" foreground="[0,0,0]" size="9" style="_cstyle270" underline="false">Disclaimer:</Font> While every effort has been made to validate the solutions in this worksheet, Waterloo Maple Inc. and the contributors are not responsible for any errors contained and are not liable for any damages resulting from the use of this material.</Text-field></Input></Group></Section><Text-field/><Text-field/></Worksheet>